<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-06-15T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-06-15T15:00:00-05:00" n="783" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d783">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">839.00/2402a: Circular Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Diplomatic Representatives
                                    in Certain Latin American Countries</gloss></hi><note n="16" xml:id="d783fn16">To those in Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile,
                                Colombia, Cuba, Ecuador, Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Uruguay, and
                                Venezuela.</note></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-06-15T16:00:00-04:00"><hi rend="italic">June 15,
                                        1921—4 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>By instruction of the President of the United States, the Military
                            Governor of Santo Domingo issued today<note n="17" xml:id="d783fn17">The
                                proclamation was issued June 14.</note> a proclamation addressed to
                            the Dominican people, in substance as follows:</p>
                        <pb facs="0963" n="839" xml:id="pg_839"/>
                        <p>[Here follows the substance of the proclamation printed on <ref target="#pg_835">page 835</ref>.]</p>
                        <p>Secure publication of this summary in all leading newspapers.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Fletcher</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>